05799nam a22008895i 9780823288984DE-B159720220329044247.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220329t20202020nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808232889847 a10.1515/97808232889842doi  a(DE-B1597)551407  a(OCoLC)1145573318  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aPOL0080002bisacsh1 aYanich, Danilo, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aBuying Reality :bPolitical Ads, Money, and Local Television News /cDanilo Yanich. 1aNew York, NY : bFordham University Press, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (256 p.) :b50  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aDonald McGannon Communication Research Center's Everett C. Parker Book Series00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- t1. Why local television news matters -- t2. A brief history of political advertising -- t3. Research method and market profiles -- t4. Political ads -- t5. Political stories -- t6. The markets -- t7. The business of news -- tConclusion. Where do we go from here? -- tAcknowledgments -- tReference list -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFrom a certain perspective, the biggest political story of 2016 was how the candidate who bought three-quarters of the political ads lost to the one whose every provocative tweet set the agenda for the day’s news coverage. With the arrival of Bot Farms, microtargeted Facebook ads, and Cambridge Analytica, isn’t the age of political ads on local TV coming to a close? You might think. But you’d be wrong to the tune of $4.4 billion just in 2016. In US elections, there’s a lot more at stake than the presidency. TV spending has gone up dramatically since 2006, for both presidential and down-ballot races for congressional seats, governorships, and state legislatures—and the 2020 campaign shows no signs of bucking this trend. When candidates don’t enjoy the name recognition and celebrity of the Presidential contenders, it’s very much business as usual. They rely on the local TV newscasts, watched by thirty million people every day—not tweets—to convey their messages to an audience more fragmented than ever. At the same time, the nationalization of news and consolidation of local stations under juggernauts like Nextstar Media and Sinclair Broadcasting means a decreasing share of time devoted to down-ballot politics—almost 90% of 2016’s local political stories focused on the Presidential race. Without coverage of local issues and races, ad buys are the only chance most candidates have to get their messages in front of a broadcast audience. On local TV news, political ads create the reality of local races—a reality that is not meant to inform voters, but to persuade them. Voters are left to their own devices to fill in the space between what the ads say—the bought reality—and what political stories used to cover.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mrz 2022) 0aAdvertising, PoliticalzUnited States. 0aLocal electionszUnited States. 0aLocal governmentzUnited States. 0aPolitical campaignszUnited States. 0aTelevision in politicszUnited States. 4aCommunications. 4aPolitical Science. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Political Process / Campaigns & Elections.2bisacsh  a2016 Presidential election.  aPolitical Ads.  acampaign finance.  acontent analysis.  alocal elections.  alocal television news.  amedia consolidation.  amoney in politics.  apolitical communication.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Political Science 2020z97831107